it if you have basic questions about mend.<br><br>First, I'm going to outline several different "styles" of healing, each appropriate to different circumstances. This stuff is mostly aimed at soloists, but can also apply in a group. After all, haven't you ever been in a group without a healer? Even with a healer or two, knowing how to best bind and mend helps your survival and can improve the mana efficiency of a group. The usual trade-off in a group is time vs.<br>mana use. It takes longer to bind wounds than using a healer, so despite the hit to the mana pool, in a hurried group bind wounds may be irrelevant.<br><br>Styles of Self-Healing for Monks: <br><br>1. "Mend only" healing <br><br>Description: This style focuses mainly on mend as a way of recouping lost hps. When you get below 3 3/4 bubbles (75% health) mash that Mend button. Anytime Mend recycles and you're at <75% health (or even a bit higher) mash. This is a pretty crude, but sometimes useful, style that ensures that you'll get the most out of Mend over time. It's also a pretty fast way to improve the Mend skill. Important note: once you get below 50% health and use Mend you're making a choice to replace hps with Mend rather than bandages. (Time vs. money.)<br><br>Typical Scenario: You will probably use this style at lower levels -- bind is relatively ineffective (and money to buy bandages is in short supply!) and you really want to max Mend skill. You might also use this style at higher levels where you're fighting low blues and below, especially if the mobs are few and far between. If this is true, you can usually keep health between about 40% and 90% without bind wounds --<br>Mend has a chance to recycle before you can find enough mobs to get you much below 50% health. I found that I stopped using this style at about level 25 or so -- the mobs got harder for a given /con and I also started hunting in dungeons, where the mobs are NOT hard to find!<br><br>2. "Normal" Bind + Mend healing<br><br>Description: This style combines binding and mend to allow maximum monster death over time. It's quite simple and is used by just about every monk I've met -- bind to over 50% hp, then use mend to get over 75% hp. Kill mobs until you are bleeding from too many orifices and repeat. The ultimate goal of any soloing monk, aside from fortune and fame, is to find a steady supply of low blue/xp-greens that can be killed without losing more than 1.5 to 2 bubbles of health. This allows you to bind plus mend up to 75%, kill a mob and drop to about 45%, kill another mob taking you to about 15-20% hp (hopefully -- sometimes I go down to about 0.1% ), sit and bind up to 50%, kill another, bind, kill another, bind, mend, kill two, bind, etc. <br><br>Typical Scenario: I've used this style most of the time post-level 25 or so. The mobs start hitting harder and bind is now good enough to heal up in a reasonable amount of time. <br><br>Tips: <br>a) Max out that bind wounds skill!! Sometime around level 20-25, I was making enough money by mugging mobs to support a bandage habit easily, but even before then I'd approached maximum skill. This is going to be harder for grouping monks, but don't neglect it -- never know when your local healer will decide to go out to an anniversary dinner with his or her spouse rather than play EQ. (Yeah, I know -- how<br>likely is that?! ) <br><br>b) Mend does not break feign death.<br><br>c) Bind wounds DOES!!! (Even though the graphic looks like you're still feigned -- aggro mobs notice these details!)<br><br>d) Bind wounds does not break sneak -- often I run behind a static mob to fight. If I get too low, I feign and when mob returns to home spot (turns around) I hit sneak and start binding. Sometimes it's a race to see who regains hps faster -- me by binding or the mob by regen. <br><br>e) Keep track of your 50% hp number so that you don't waste bandages.<br><br>f) You can bind successfully from anything <50% hp. This allows you to bandage up to over 50%. Example: I have 1000 max hp and finish slapping on a bandage at 499hp with bind skill of 180. I get 45 hp, taking me to 544hp -- 54.4% hp.<br><br>g) How many hp per bandage? No, it's not really (bind skill)/4 rounded down. While you bandage you regenerate hps, so the number is a bit higher. As a human monk, I use a rule of thumb: hp/bandage = bind/4 + 2. So at skill 200, I get about 52 hp per bandage. (50 for the bind, 2 for the regen in the time it takes to apply the band-aid.) Iksars will have a higher result due to their better regen rate. Regen rates are also higher (I hear) beyond level 50.<br><br>h) Up to level 40, a monk with no HP gear or buffs and maxed skill in bind will take about 9 bandages to go from 0% to 50% hp. Each level (up to level 40) gives 5 skill gains = 1.25 hp per bandage and 23 or so hps. Half health increases roughly 11.5 hp per level, so the increase of 1.25 hp per bandage will cover this in 9 bandages. Now unless you're a Kamikaze Monk (TM), you probably feign or stop fighting at about<br>10-20% hp. So you will have about 30-40% hp to bind using this style. This is about 5-7 bandages. A pretty good way to figure out how many bandages to pack on those wonderful outings to LOIO.<br><br>i) None of this is accurate for bind skill > 200. This allows you to bind many more hps per band-aid and bind + mend to > 95%. <br><br><br>3. "Tough mob" bind + mend style<br><br>Description: When I'm fighting a borderline monster, where I'd rather have full hps, but am too antsy to wait it out, I use a trick to max out my available hps. I can get up to 84-89% hp every time instead of 75-80%. That extra 100+ hps is very useful against heavy hitters! <br><br>How to do it:<br>a) Starting from below 50%, remove your +HP gear.<br>b) Doing this will cause you to drop those extra hps. Because of this, make sure you're in a safe location and DON'T TAKE OFF ANYTHING THAT WILL CAUSE YOUR HPS TO GO BELOW 0 -- YOU WILL DIE! Sorry about the shouting -- but you really didn't want to die that way... <br>b1) If you're too low to remove all your +HP gear, bind up until you can and then remove the gear.<br>c) Bind up to over 50% of your new maximum hps.<br>d) Put on your +HP gear.<br>e) Mash the Mend button.<br>f) Voila! You're should be significantly over 75% (depending on how much +HP gear you have). <br><br>How it works: This isn't rocket science, just a bit of elementary algebra. (Your brain starts to melt!) <br>baseline hps (without +HP gear) = b<br>extra hps (from +HP gear) = y<br>current hps = h<br>max hps = b + y<br>bind + mend = 75% of max hps = 0.75(b + y) <== using style #2, "normal" bind +<br>mend<br><br>Step a) Your max hps goes from (b + y) => b<br>c) Your hps (h) go to 50% of max: h = 0.5b<br>d) You add +HP gear: h = 0.5b + y<br>e) Mend and get +25% hps: h => h + 0.25(b + y) = 0.75b + 1.25y<br>Notice that this is 0.5y more than "normal" method!<br>Example: I have 927 base hp with 215hp from my equipment. (Total max hp = 1142.) Using "normal" bind + wound I can get to 75% max hp = 855hp. Using "tough mob" bind + wound I can get to 0.75*927 + 1.25*215 = 963hp = 108 extra hps.<br><br>Note that this method uses more bandages!<br><br>4. "Pessimistic" bind + mend style<br><br>Description: This one's for the real "reaches" -- those mobs that you know deep down inside are probably going to kick your sorry butt. I always use this for ID fear-kiting mobs that would crush me toe-to-toe. I never like to depend on ID actually working... Simply use the "tough mob" style as above, then sit and wait<br>for mend to recycle. Using this I can go into a fight in 6 minutes with 100% hp and full mend. <br><br>Notes: <br>a) Using the "tough mob" style allows me to regen all the way up to 100% in the six minutes it takes mend to recycle. I bind and mend up to 963 hp as in the example in #3 and then sit. My current regen is 3hp per 6-second "tick" while sitting, so after 6 minutes I've regained 180hp, taking me to one point more than my max! <br>b) If the fight's going well I don't mend, and wait until after the fight to bind + mend. <br>c) If the fight's close I mend as soon as I drop below 75% (3.75 bubbles). This will ensure that mend is available again as soon as possible.<br>d) If the fight's not going well at all, I feign! <br><br>Although much of this info is known my most monks, I hope that having it all in one place will be useful. Comments and additions more than welcome!<br><br>/salute Monks!<br><br>Feodor Dustyoasski<br>40th Level Practicing-Medicine-Without-A-License<br>The Seventh Hammer<br><br><br>Edited by: Zinj at: 4/26/01 9:27:17 am<br> <br>Zinj<br>Moderator<br>Posts: 1258<br>(4/26/01 9:22:05 am)<br>Reply | Edit | Del  Re: How to bind yourself above 50%<br>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br> *consolidated from a similar thread*<br>Editor Zinj<br><br>---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br><br>sammyd11<br>Monk<br>posts: 2<br>(2/19/01 7:50:49 am)<br>Reply | Edit | Del All<br>Soloing with very little downtime<br><br>In theory. Here's my strategy as an Iksar Monk soloing in LOIO, or anywhere with lots of monsters that con blue to you. You must have Feign Death (lv17) and I have sucessfully used this technique up to lv23 and see no reason it will stop working.<br><br>First, your Bind Wounds skill needs to be good. At lv20 mine broke 100, and that was plenty for this technique. Second, your FD has to be good. Mine also broke 100 at lv20 (keep mashin' that button) and I get very few "fallen to the ground"s.<br><br>You start off the hunt at full health with mend, so pick a blue that you usually have trouble with, or even a black. After the first battle, you should pick blues from that point on.<br><br>Fight until your health is two bubs left - this is where you have to start paying attention. The rules:<br><br>1) When your health reaches 1 1/2 bubs, make a decision - if your're real close to<br>winning, don't hit mend and keep fighting. If you're far from winning, but can win, hit<br>mend and finish him. If you're going to lose, don't waste the health and FD now.<br><br>2) If you fall to 1 bub and have used mend, FD repeatedly until he's off you - no<br>more fighting! If you have 1 bub and still have mend, take about 1 more good hit<br>before poking mend. Maybe he'll have a bad streak and you can save mend and still<br>finish him.<br><br>3) When the battle's over (either he's dead or you're FD), hit sneak and start binding<br>wounds. Sneak reduces your aggro radius so that very few wanderers will attack.<br>When you've bound to near 1/2, make sure you time it to get that last BW when<br>you're just below half.<br><br>If the battle went well, you should have mend and be at 1/2 health after only a few BWs. Even if you've used mend, go fight another blue! I found that I could usually kill 3-4 blues with this strategy before using mend. <br><br>After you use mend and are at 1/2, pick a weak blue - one that you know you can usually kill without using mend. You might have to use FD, but that's what it's for! After killing 2 or 3 easy blues this way, mend would usually pop and I could go back to the harder blues again. I have found I can usually hunt in LOIO until I've used up my bandages with no downtime except while I am Binding Wounds. Sure, I have to FD and don't get to kill all the mobs I attack, but at least I'm fighting and not sitting crouched at the Windmill. Since you're solo, the Exp is fantastic - I get 2/3s a blue bub from the hard blues and 1/3 from the easys. I would get 2-3 red bubs off of a 60 bandage hunting seesion. Good hunting to ya! <br> <br>Zinj<br>Moderator<br>Posts: 1259<br>(4/26/01 9:30:13 am)<br>Reply | Edit | Del  Re: How to bind yourself above 50%<br>--------------------------------------